<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-321-410  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 321 410.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  May 29 1989 v3 n22 p36(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>AF's Cassity pilots C3I for Joint Chiefs of Staff. (Air Force'sLt. Gen. James Cassity - director of command, control,communications and intelligence)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Air Force Lt.andP;  Gen James Cassity has the new job of director ofcommand, control, communications and intelligence with the JointChief of Staff.andP;  Cassity will use his knowledge of computersystems to increase the Pentagon's use of commercial equipment.andO;As commander of the Air Force Communications Command, Cassitysigned off on the largest Defense Department computer purchase inhistory, the $930 million contract awarded to AT andamp; T for up to21,000 minicomputer systems.andP;  He believes that the military willbe buying more and more off-the-shelf gear as time goes on.andO;Military-standard equipment takes too long to develop and updatecompared to commercial development, he said.andP;  The Pentagon is alsoleaning more towards ready-made computers because of tighterbudgets.andP;  Cassity does not see Ada becoming the sole language usedin military software.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Air ForceMilitaryPurchasesManagementPromotion of Employee.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Cassity, James (portrait)Person:    Cassity, James (management).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>